entry.title: [FilesF2] Add util functions to handle tree naming difference
entry.content:
There are 2 differences between the old tree and the new tree:

1. `insanceof` check against `DirectoryTree/DirectoryItem` won't

work with the new tree, we need to wrap the check into a util

function to make sure it works with both implementations.

2. `selectedItem` property v.s. `focusedItem`: the old tree uses

`selectedItem` property to get the current focused item, which is

quite confusing, that's why the new tree updates the name to

`focusedItem`, we need to create a util function to handle this

difference.



Note: adding `type_name` for DirectoryTree and DirectoryItem to

prevent the usage of `instanceof`, because importing the type

itself might trigger circular import issue.

entry.title: CrOS Settings: Separating first and subsequent lifetime metrics.
entry.content:
Separating "ChromeOS.Settings.NumUniqueSettingsChanged.DeviceLifetime"

into ".FirstWeek" and ".SubsequentWeeks". Assuming that users will change more Settings in the first week to customize their device to their liking, so to understand the data better, we will separate the data into 2 histograms. This will help us understand the true value of how many Settings users will change on average, without the data from the first week skewing the results.



This CL is a follow-up to b/280480850.



BUG=b/281946097

TEST=

Manual:

A)

1. Run ChromeOS with OOBE. Take the onboarding steps.

2. Open Settings.

2. Change a Setting that we are recording the name of, such as

switching the toggle for Do Not Disturb.

3. Close the Settings app, open your browser and search

"chrome://histograms", then find the histogram

"ChromeOS.Settings.NumUniqueSettingsChanged.DeviceLifetime.FirstWeek". There

will be one count added to the respective bucket. The bucket

represents the number of unique changes made over the device's

lifetime.

4. Repeat steps 1-3 with different Settings changed each time. The

histogram will each time record the correct number of accumulated

unique Settings changed.

B)

1. Repeat 'A' after a week time has passed.

2. The corresponding histogram will now be called

"ChromeOS.Settings.NumUniqueSettingsChanged.DeviceLifetime.SunsequentWeeks"

NOTE: The recorded count has now been reset, meaning that if we repeat `Do not disturb` toggle

flip after the first week, we will now record it again in

histogram ".SubsequentWeeks".

3. No data will be added to ".FirstWeek" after the first week has

passed.



--gtest_filter="*SettingsUserActionTrackerTest*"



Unittest: DISPLAY=:20 out/Default/unit_tests

entry.title: [css-flex] Try a more conservative intrinsic sizing algorithm
entry.content:
Our first attempt at a better algorithm was not compatible with the web.

This version gives behavior closer to what is currently shipping in all

browsers.



The difference in this version affects only single-line row containers'

min-content sizes. For such containers where no items are growing from

their flex basis to their desired min contribution, an item's final

contribution to the container's min-content size is (1) its flex-basis

if the item has a 0 flex factor in whichever direction it wants to go

(shrink if flex-basis > min-content contribution, grow otherwise);

otherwise: (2) its min-content contribution.



This will probably only be enabled for a few days, but will give us good

compat data even so.

entry.title: Remove the version in android_toolchain CIPD path
entry.content:
Including the toolchain version in the CIPD package path means that

downstream rollers observe major revision changes to the NDK as

completely new CIPD packages, e.g.



chromium/third_party/android_toolchain/r23c/android_toolchain

chromium/third_party/android_toolchain/r25c/android_toolchain



This would result in every downstream repository observing a roller

breakage on every such update, which is undesirable. Consolidate the

toolchain path to always exist at:



chromium/third_party/android_toolchain/android_toolchain



So that only the 'version' attribute of the package is updated and

rollers can update the package without gardener intervention.

entry.title: [PDF OCR] Maybe create OCR service during PdfAccessibilityTree CTOR
entry.content:
Create `ocr_service_` if it's not created but AXMode has `kPDFOcr` for

PDF OCR when `PdfAccessibilityTree` is being created.



When the PDF OCR pref is set, AXMode gets set for PDF OCR and sent to

PDF renderer during its `WebContents` creation. `PdfAccessibilityTree`

then receives this AXMode in `AccessibilityModeChanged()` and creates

`ocr_service_`. However, it's possible that `PdfAccessibilityTree`

starts observing for AXMode through `content::RenderFrameObserver`

after the browser sent AXMode to PDF renderer due to a timing issue.

This CL implements a workaround fix for this timing issue.
